<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910523-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>910523-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Entergy Corp.:   Pact With State Regulators   Is Reached on Grand Gulf</HL><DATE>05/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   ETR</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)</IN><NS>NUCLEAR POWER, ENERGY (NUK)</NS><RE>ALASKA (AK)LOUISIANA (LA)MISSISSIPPI (MS)</RE><LP>   Entergy Corp. said it reached a settlement with regulatorsin three states lowering its return on equity on the GrandGulf 1 nuclear unit to 13% from 14%, effective retroactivelyto April 1990. Regulators had sought a reduction to at least12%.   The New Orleans-based utility said that because theagreement is retroactive, it will include a refund and othercredits to customers that will reduce 1991 rates by $61million. The refund will be divided among customers inArkansas, Louisiana, Mississippi. The pact will also lower1992 revenue by $27 million.</LP><TEXT>   In addition, the agreement provides for an increase, to$220 million of principal from $93 million of principal, inthe amount of the decommissioning fund that will be used todismantle the Grand Gulf facility sometime after the year2022.   The settlement proposal will be submitted to a FederalEnergy Regulatory Commission administrative law judge inearly June and is expected to be approved by the fullcommission this summer, Entergy said.</TEXT></DOC>